Start of relevant regressions

‘Naive’ TWFE and Bacon Decomposition

First I will run a naive TWFE model, controlling for state and year fixed effects. The first model will have clustered SE while the second will have wild cluster bootstrapped standard errors. These regressions have not been weighted by state population!

naive <- feols(log_rate ~ treatment | scode + year, data = guns)
naive_boot <- boottest(naive, clustid = c("scode"), B = 9999, param = "treatment", seed = 1)
msummary(list('Clustered SE' = naive, 'Wild Cluster Bootstrap' = naive_boot),coef_rename = c('1*treatment = 0' = 'treatment'),estimate = "{estimate}", statistic = c("conf.int", "p = {p.value}"), 
            gof_omit = 'R2 Pseudo|AIC|BIC|Log.Lik.|R2 Within|R2 Adj.')

Now I will look at the Bacon decomposition of the naive TWFE model. I.e., how the cannonical 2x2 did has been weighted.

df_bacon <- bacon(log_rate ~ treatment, data = guns,
                  id_var = 'scode',
                  time_var = 'year')
##                       type  weight  avg_est
## 1 Earlier vs Later Treated 0.04104 -0.02555
## 2 Later vs Earlier Treated 0.04635  0.08371
## 3     Treated vs Untreated 0.91260  0.19809
coef_bacon <- sum(df_bacon$estimate * df_bacon$weight)
print(paste("Weighted sum of decomposition =", round(coef_bacon, 4)))
## [1] "Weighted sum of decomposition = 0.1836"
ggplot(df_bacon) +
  aes(x = weight, y = estimate, shape = factor(type)) +
  labs(x = "Weight", y = "Estimate", shape = "Type") +
  geom_point()

As we can see, the “good” treatment effects have the highest weight. Im assuming that the estimate at 0.0 is Virginia.

TWFE with population weights and controls

First I will run the basic TWFE model, but now with weights that are equal to the population of the year 2004. I need to check if this is the correct way to specify weights in feols (reminder). Finally, I will wild cluster bootstrap the standard errors for the coefficient of interest.

twfe <- feols(log_rate ~ treatment | scode + year,weights = ~pop_const, data = guns)
twfe_boot <- boottest(twfe, clustid = "scode", B = 9999, param = "treatment", seed = 1000)

Furthermore, I will add two control variables: per_rural & per_white and interact them with year fixed effects. Again, wild-cluster standard errors will be used for the coefficient of interest.

twfe_c <- feols(log_rate ~ treatment + per_rural*factor(year) + per_white*factor(year) | scode + year,
                weights = ~pop_const,data = guns)
## Variables 'per_rural', 'factor(year)2000' and 21 others have been removed because of collinearity (see $collin.var).
twfec_boot <- boottest(twfe_c, clustid = c("scode"), B = 9999, param = "treatment", seed = 1)

As can be seen, in the first regression without controls, repealing the policy leaded to an aprox. increase in handgun related suicides by 21.5% (need to use \((e^{a-1})*100\%\) to get correct % change). When adding the percentage of white population and percentage of people living in rural areas the estimate drops down to around 12.5%.

Event-study; checking pre-trends

Here I run into problems because I cant seem to get the correct wild cluster bootstrap standard errors for event time estimates.

pre_twfe = feols(log_rate ~ i(stimetotreatment, treatment_group, ref = -1) | scode + year, weights = ~pop_const, data = guns)
iplot(pre_twfe,pt.join = TRUE, ref = -1)

This is with clustered SE. Even though the confidence intervals are all around 0 in the few years leading to the repeal of the policy I find it troubling that there seems to be a linear upward trend throughout the whole time period. We will get back to this while using the Sant’Anna & Callaway model because strangly this linear trend dissapears when using their estimator.

Now, I will try to run a for loop which will bootstrap all of the estimates.

coef_name <- names(coef(pre_twfe))

})

Since they are -11 and -15 I am not troubled because at the bin of the distribution there is a smaller number of obs. Important note, standard errors are generated through a multiplier bootstrap method they talk about in their paper. Finally, I have weighted the regression by state population. However, I get the following error message: Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1.. I do not know what this means, but my results are generated without problems.

Placebo tests - Do we find something we shouldnt & is there some form of substition going on?

I will now run two different TWFE models. I will change the dependent variable to be all other forms of suicide (without codes X72,X73,X74 -> i.e., no firearms included) and only long-gun related suicides. Small note, since the long-gun rates are suppressed for many states I downloaded the combination of codes X72-X74 and then calculated \(X72+X74+X73 - X72-X74\) to get the true incidence of long-gun related suicides (X73). Furthermore, these values are sometimes below 1, making it impractical to use the natural log. To surpass this problem I added 1 to every row such that I can use the natural log.

twfe_placebo <- feols(log_other ~ treatment | scode + year, weights = ~pop_const, data = guns)
twfep_boot <- boottest(twfe_placebo, clustid = c("scode"), B = 9999, param = "treatment", seed = 1)
twfe_long <- feols(log_long ~ treatment | scode + year, weights = ~pop_const,data = guns)
twfel_boot <- boottest(twfe_long, clustid = c("scode"), B = 9999, param = "treatment", seed = 1)
msummary(list('All other' = twfep_boot, 'Long guns' = twfel_boot),
         coef_rename = c('1*treatment = 0' = 'Treatment'),
          estimate = "{estimate}", statistic = c("conf.int", "p = {p.value}"), stars = TRUE, 
            gof_omit = 'R2 Pseudo|AIC|BIC|Log.Lik.|R2 Within|R2 Adj.')

p = 0.160 p = 0.591

+ p < 0.1, * p < 0.05, ** p < 0.01, *** p < 0.001

As we can see from the regression results, coeficients are negative.The negative point estimate makes sense, it basically says that on average people commit suicide less with other methods once a handgun purchase delay law is repealed. It is assuring that I do not find a statistically significant coefficient.

Conclusion

To conclude, I can see that there is evidence of a positive hike in handgun-related suicides after the repeal of restrictive firearm purchase policies. There is still a lot of work to be done on this research question but the preliminary findings are reassuring. The biggest problem I have is wildcluster bootstraping the event study estimates and understanding if I am facing any problems with pre-trends!
